NOTES TO THE GEORGICS.

‘ placidi straverunt aequora venti.' Orpheus is said to have charmed the winds by his music, Hor. Od. 1. 12. 10.

487. legem, ‘ condition? See on 1. 493 below. To this was added the further condition that Orpheus should not look back, until he had passed the boundaries of Hell. Ovid in his more de- tailed account ffllet. 10. 50) mentions this expressly :—

‘ Hanc simul et legem Rhodopeius accipit heros, ne flectat retro sua lumina, donec Avernas exierit valles, aut irrita dona futura.'

493, 494. foedera, = legem in l. 487, ¹ conditions ' defined as in a bond or treaty between Orpheus and Pluto. Cp. ‘leges et soedera,’ 1. 60. fragor, ‘ crash’ of thunder, probably the signal os Eurydice's return to the shades. stagnis properly refers to the actual lake Avernus in Campania, supposed to be the entrance to Hades (l. 467 n.).
